{
  "doc_id": "13054",
  "text": "Although few vasopressinergic fibers innervate the dorsal hippocampus [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] , both V1a and V1b receptors are abundant in this structure [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . The CA2 hippocampal subfield is particularly relevant to study central AVP actions. Indeed, although the V1a receptor is mainly distributed in the dentate gyrus and on dispersed cells in the three CA areas of the dorsal and ventral hippocampus [CITATION_5] , the V1b receptor is mainly expressed in the dorsal CA2 area [CITATION_6] . Accordingly, implication of the CA2 area in the AVP actions on social behavior and episodic memory has been suggested [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] . CA2 is not simply a transition area between CA1 and CA3 but also possesses a number of specific characteristics. Functionally, it is resistant to temporal epilepsy [CITATION_9] and might be involved in the onset of schizophrenia [CITATION_10] . Moreover, this area displays unique anatomical (neuronal morphology and expression of specific proteins) and electrophysiological features indicating that it is engaged differently by synaptic inputs as compared to CA3 or CA1 (see [CITATION_11] ). Furthermore, CA2 constitutes the key structure of a disynaptic cortico-hippocampal loop [CITATION_12] [CITATION_13] , in which the CA2 pyramidal cells are directly activated by cortical afferents, bypassing the dentate gyrus and CA3 intermediates. The presence of specific synaptic circuitry in CA2 is also indicated by the distinct morphology and electrophysiological characteristics of parvalbumin immunoreactive interneurons [CITATION_14] .",
